00:16:43.090 --> 00:16:45.530
to position.

00:16:45.530 --> 00:16:47.950
So many people
were saying c here.

00:16:47.950 --> 00:16:51.660
And actually, this is
where the concentration

00:16:51.660 --> 00:16:56.420
will remain exactly constant
over this next delta t.

00:16:56.420 --> 00:16:57.861
And of course, if
we want to know

00:16:57.861 --> 00:17:00.360
about what the concentration
is going to do for a long time,

00:17:00.360 --> 00:17:01.950
then we have to do
something more subtle.

00:17:01.950 --> 00:17:03.700
But if we want to how
the concentration is

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:08.730
changing right now, then we
just look at the curvature.

00:17:08.730 --> 00:17:11.139
And indeed, the curvature
here is maximal.

00:17:14.599 --> 00:17:18.131
So concentration
DCDT at this point,

00:17:18.131 --> 00:17:19.839
is it going to be
greater or less than 0?

00:17:19.839 --> 00:17:22.770
Ready three, two, one.

00:17:22.770 --> 00:17:24.770
PROFESSOR: Less than 0, right?

00:17:24.770 --> 00:17:28.413
Now, it's true that only the
curvature at a particular point

00:17:28.413 --> 00:17:31.760
and matter is to know how the
concentrations going to change

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:33.191
over this next delta t.

00:17:33.191 --> 00:17:34.690
But if you want to
know about what's

00:17:34.690 --> 00:17:36.150
going to happen over
longer periods of time,

00:17:36.150 --> 00:17:38.566
than you have to worry about
more of the global structure.

00:17:38.566 --> 00:17:42.650
And what's true is that this
local maximum may quickly

00:17:42.650 --> 00:17:44.374
go away.

00:17:44.374 --> 00:17:46.790
So you don't have to wait very
long before this thing gets

00:17:46.790 --> 00:17:53.590
smooth and then DCDT will--
the magnitude will go to 0.

00:17:53.590 --> 00:18:00.810
And sometimes this big hump
will stick around longer,

00:18:00.810 --> 00:18:02.940
but because of the
curvature, this

00:18:02.940 --> 00:18:06.830
has the maximal
magnitude of DCDT.

00:18:10.972 --> 00:18:12.680
And it makes sense
that the concentration

00:18:12.680 --> 00:18:15.680
is going to go down because the
net flux here is to the right

00:18:15.680 --> 00:18:16.635
and to the left.

00:18:16.635 --> 00:18:18.510
And so there's a net
flux, particles leaving,

00:18:18.510 --> 00:18:20.010
concentration is
going to come down.

00:18:23.590 --> 00:18:28.730
Now are there any questions
about what we've said?

00:18:28.730 --> 00:18:31.870
If you find this
discussion confusing,

00:18:31.870 --> 00:18:35.560
I would strongly encourage you
to get together with a friend

00:18:35.560 --> 00:18:38.485
and just draw some
random lines, curves,

00:18:38.485 --> 00:18:39.860
and just make sure
you understand

00:18:39.860 --> 00:18:42.197
where diffusion is going to
pull things and so forth.

00:18:44.940 --> 00:18:45.505
No questions?

00:18:55.030 --> 00:18:56.780
All right, I just want
to say a few things

00:18:56.780 --> 00:19:01.120
about the so-called French
flag model in development.

00:19:01.120 --> 00:19:05.709
This is perhaps the most famous.

00:19:05.709 --> 00:19:07.875
Does everybody know what
the French flag looks like?

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:12.860
What's that?

00:19:12.860 --> 00:19:13.470
All right.

00:19:13.470 --> 00:19:16.430
There are three stripes
and some orientation.

00:19:16.430 --> 00:19:19.310
No, but the idea here is
just that a simple way

00:19:19.310 --> 00:19:23.610
to specify a structure
across one axis

00:19:23.610 --> 00:19:28.280
is to have a defusing chemical
or generally a protein.

00:19:28.280 --> 00:19:31.040
And then based on the
concentration of that protein

00:19:31.040 --> 00:19:34.430
or morphogen, you can just
have the tissue read out

00:19:34.430 --> 00:19:37.500
what it's supposed to be,
or what it's supposed to do.

00:19:37.500 --> 00:19:40.720
So the idea here
is that, you have

00:19:40.720 --> 00:19:45.620
some morphogen that starts
maybe on one end of an embryo

00:19:45.620 --> 00:19:48.340
and then diffuses.

00:19:48.340 --> 00:19:50.790
So we end up with
some curve that

00:19:50.790 --> 00:19:55.090
tells us about the
morphogen concentration

00:19:55.090 --> 00:19:57.730
as a function of position.

00:19:57.730 --> 00:19:59.450
This is a functional position.

00:19:59.450 --> 00:20:03.620
So this is along the embryo.

00:20:03.620 --> 00:20:06.040
Now the general challenge in
the context of development

00:20:06.040 --> 00:20:10.900
is asking-- we
started this embryo

00:20:10.900 --> 00:20:13.130
with many different
cells, they're

00:20:13.130 --> 00:20:15.870
all genetically identical,
and they all start out maybe

00:20:15.870 --> 00:20:18.050
without any positional
information.

00:20:18.050 --> 00:20:19.360
They don't know where they are.

00:20:19.360 --> 00:20:20.735
But what that
means is they don't

00:20:20.735 --> 00:20:25.000
know they need to develop into
a head or a tail or something

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:26.630
in between.

00:20:26.630 --> 00:20:31.920
Now what often happens is that
you can have a deposition often

00:20:31.920 --> 00:20:35.100
by the mother so you have a
maternal deposition of, say,

00:20:35.100 --> 00:20:39.170
RNA that leads to expression
of some morphogen on one end

00:20:39.170 --> 00:20:40.134
and then it diffuses.

00:20:40.134 --> 00:20:41.550
And based on the
concentration you

00:20:41.550 --> 00:20:46.120
can say what part of the body
you should be developing into.

00:20:46.120 --> 00:20:49.410
So the idea is you just
have these thresholds that

00:20:49.410 --> 00:20:51.570
might be some M1, M2.

00:20:55.140 --> 00:20:59.870
All right, now all
the cells over here

00:20:59.870 --> 00:21:03.030
know that they should
maybe develop into a head.

00:21:03.030 --> 00:21:06.830
Over here, they're going to
develop into the mid body.

00:21:06.830 --> 00:21:10.420
And over down here it could
be the low body, for example.

00:21:10.420 --> 00:21:14.270
So just from the
concentration that a cell

00:21:14.270 --> 00:21:15.840
feels at a particular location.

00:21:15.840 --> 00:21:18.260
So if you had a cell
right here, you just

00:21:18.260 --> 00:21:21.540
say OK the concentration of
morphogens between M1 and M2

00:21:21.540 --> 00:21:26.770
and then from that you know
what l you're supposed be.

00:21:26.770 --> 00:21:35.500
Now if you have no
degradation within the body.

00:21:35.500 --> 00:21:43.950
Let's just imagine you
say, that at one end is 0.

00:21:43.950 --> 00:21:48.380
We're told morphogen
concentration is M0.

00:21:48.380 --> 00:21:51.810
And let's say that the other
end, we know the morphogen

00:21:51.810 --> 00:21:53.560
concentration is going to be 0.

00:21:53.560 --> 00:21:58.520
Let's say there's a lot
of degradation at an end.

00:21:58.520 --> 00:22:00.480
If there's no
degradation in between,

00:22:00.480 --> 00:22:04.620
what should the profile
look like given these?

00:22:04.620 --> 00:22:05.580
So, no.

00:22:08.990 --> 00:22:09.490
All right.

00:22:09.490 --> 00:22:13.960
So just diffusion with
these boundary conditions.

00:22:13.960 --> 00:22:17.030
I'm going to draw some
options and hopefully you

00:22:17.030 --> 00:22:19.970
can close your eyes and
imagine what it should be.

00:22:19.970 --> 00:22:26.350
All right, we know that starts
out M0 over L is equal to 0.

00:22:42.220 --> 00:22:45.930
Is it closer to A, B, C, or D?

00:22:56.450 --> 00:22:59.030
Do you understand
what I'm asking?

00:22:59.030 --> 00:22:59.800
Yes.

00:22:59.800 --> 00:23:01.360
AUDIENCE: That is
a steady state.

00:23:01.360 --> 00:23:04.620
PROFESSOR: This is the steady
state concentration profile

00:23:04.620 --> 00:23:09.390
of the morphogen given there's
no degradation in the interior.

00:23:09.390 --> 00:23:12.270
Ready three, two, one.

00:23:15.410 --> 00:23:16.020
All right.

00:23:16.020 --> 00:23:19.100
So at least a majority are
agreeing it's going to be B.

00:23:19.100 --> 00:23:23.940
Although, there's a significant
minority that's saying A.

00:23:23.940 --> 00:23:27.030
This is why I'm bring
this up because, we're

00:23:27.030 --> 00:23:29.100
so used to seeing
exponential profiles

00:23:29.100 --> 00:23:31.610
and think that you should
always be getting them.

00:23:31.610 --> 00:23:34.860
And I want to be clear why
it's an exponential profile.

00:23:34.860 --> 00:23:36.940
That's the thing we start
with, and for example

00:23:36.940 --> 00:23:39.670
this model in [INAUDIBLE] book.

00:23:39.670 --> 00:23:43.140
Noori's book, you get
exponential profiles

00:23:43.140 --> 00:23:47.140
as a result of first
order degradation.

00:23:47.140 --> 00:23:51.390
Whereas if you don't have any
degradation in the interior,

00:23:51.390 --> 00:23:58.840
then we say, OK, DCD-- well,
do we want to use C or M now?

00:23:58.840 --> 00:24:00.610
We'll use M, just
because now we're

00:24:00.610 --> 00:24:03.130
thinking very particularly
for morphogen.

00:24:03.130 --> 00:24:04.585
All so DMDT.

00:24:11.840 --> 00:24:15.290
We want to know the
steady state profile.

00:24:15.290 --> 00:24:16.535
We set this thing equal to 0.

00:24:21.110 --> 00:24:22.920
Integrate twice.

00:24:22.920 --> 00:24:25.790
Right, so we're going to get--
morphogen profile should just

00:24:25.790 --> 00:24:28.914
be some Ax plus B, OK?

00:24:35.310 --> 00:24:37.200
My line's kind of
crappy, I'm sorry.

00:24:41.510 --> 00:24:43.780
However, when we have
first order degradation,

00:24:43.780 --> 00:24:46.100
then we get these
exponential profiles.

00:24:49.350 --> 00:24:52.750
Are there any questions about--?

00:24:52.750 --> 00:24:56.710
AUDIENCE: Is it possible
to have [INAUDIBLE]?

00:24:56.710 --> 00:24:59.420
PROFESSOR: Yeah, right.

00:24:59.420 --> 00:25:01.659
What does this require?

00:25:01.659 --> 00:25:05.603
AUDIENCE: The morphogen
is generated into halves.

00:25:05.603 --> 00:25:07.876
X equals 0 and then--

00:25:07.876 --> 00:25:09.000
PROFESSOR: Degraded it at--

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:09.900
AUDIENCE: Disappearing.

00:25:09.900 --> 00:25:10.566
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:25:10.566 --> 00:25:11.820
Right.

00:25:11.820 --> 00:25:16.430
That's what I'm saying, is that
when I said that at the end

00:25:16.430 --> 00:25:19.940
it was a 0, this means that we
have degradation at this point.

00:25:19.940 --> 00:25:24.470
Any time that the morphogen
reaches the end of the embryos,

00:25:24.470 --> 00:25:25.400
it gets degraded.

00:25:28.100 --> 00:25:31.420
So it's not degradation inside
if it's only degradation here.

00:25:31.420 --> 00:25:34.100
And this of course a situation
where you have constant flux

00:25:34.100 --> 00:25:36.860
throughout the embryo,
constant rate of production

00:25:36.860 --> 00:25:40.100
of the morphogen, constant
rate of degradation over here.

00:25:44.690 --> 00:25:47.490
But when you have this
first order degradation--

00:25:47.490 --> 00:25:51.430
if we're told that
instead-- well, maybe.

00:26:05.300 --> 00:26:12.000
So, if in addition
to having diffusion,

00:26:12.000 --> 00:26:15.180
you also have this
first order degradation.

00:26:15.180 --> 00:26:17.910
Now remember M is a function
of both x and t, right?

00:26:17.910 --> 00:26:23.890
And this is the situation where
we get exponential profiles.

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:27.500
Now in Murray's book,
he often discusses

00:26:27.500 --> 00:26:32.310
this where the
boundary condition

00:26:32.310 --> 00:26:37.540
is that you have some
concentration M0 at one end.

00:26:37.540 --> 00:26:44.002
And then we get an
exponential profile here.

00:26:44.002 --> 00:26:45.710
What was the characteristic
length scale?

00:26:52.320 --> 00:26:54.930
This is something we should
be able to figure out.

00:27:03.590 --> 00:27:07.160
You should, of course, be
able to solve the equations,

00:27:07.160 --> 00:27:10.590
but you should be
able to figure it out

00:27:10.590 --> 00:27:13.670
from our favorite approach
of dimensional analysis.

00:27:13.670 --> 00:27:17.040
What's the units of things here?

00:27:17.040 --> 00:27:20.740
So units of D is what?

00:27:20.740 --> 00:27:21.910
Length squared over time.

00:27:28.600 --> 00:27:29.500
Units of alpha?

00:27:34.930 --> 00:27:38.220
So this is a morphogen
concentration over a time.

00:27:38.220 --> 00:27:40.812
This is a morphogen
concentration.

00:27:40.812 --> 00:27:42.395
So this thing has
to be one over time.

00:27:46.110 --> 00:27:47.620
So the length
scale is then going

00:27:47.620 --> 00:27:58.960
to have to go as the
square root of D over L.

00:27:58.960 --> 00:28:01.790
And indeed, if you solve it,
it's exactly equal to that,

00:28:01.790 --> 00:28:04.199
but this dimensional
analysis just told us

00:28:04.199 --> 00:28:05.490
that it had to scale like that.

00:28:08.350 --> 00:28:10.780
So this is telling us about
a characteristic length

00:28:10.780 --> 00:28:13.930
of which this morphogen
profile is going to fall off.

00:28:13.930 --> 00:28:20.100
This is the
characteristic length L.

00:28:20.100 --> 00:28:22.860
Incidentally, you'll
see many cases

00:28:22.860 --> 00:28:24.800
of things that look like this.

00:28:24.800 --> 00:28:28.060
So if there's first
order rate that's

00:28:28.060 --> 00:28:32.940
something is either degraded
or is uptaken or whatnot, then

00:28:32.940 --> 00:28:37.450
together with diffusion, you'll
get an exponential profile

00:28:37.450 --> 00:28:39.964
with a [INAUDIBLE] length scale
that's given by this ratio.

00:28:39.964 --> 00:28:41.880
And you'll see this in
many different contexts

00:28:41.880 --> 00:28:46.890
of, for example, nutrients
going into a biofilm.

00:28:46.890 --> 00:28:49.780
If you have cells
picking up nutrients

00:28:49.780 --> 00:28:53.340
then it's not that
it's being degraded,

00:28:53.340 --> 00:28:55.162
but it's being imported.

00:28:55.162 --> 00:28:56.620
Then you'll have
a similar process.

00:29:02.800 --> 00:29:07.310
This is a nice, fine situation
except for what was the problem

00:29:07.310 --> 00:29:08.520
that [INAUDIBLE] pointed out?

00:29:11.490 --> 00:29:12.187
It's not robust.

00:29:12.187 --> 00:29:13.395
It's not robust against what?

00:29:18.200 --> 00:29:20.500
Initial condition.

00:29:20.500 --> 00:29:24.630
Yes, but I think we have to be
a little more specific on that.

00:29:24.630 --> 00:29:26.420
Right, it's not robust
to changes in M0.

00:29:36.240 --> 00:29:39.760
Incidentally, in
most context, I think

00:29:39.760 --> 00:29:41.300
for mathematical
simplicity, it's

00:29:41.300 --> 00:29:45.820
useful to just have a banner
condition where M0 is constant.

00:29:45.820 --> 00:29:50.560
But in general, is
that what the mother is

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:53.070
going to be fixing necessarily?

00:29:53.070 --> 00:29:54.820
What would the mother
typically be fixing?

00:29:58.370 --> 00:29:59.625
What was that?

00:29:59.625 --> 00:30:00.960
AUDIENCE: Production rate.

00:30:00.960 --> 00:30:02.824
PROFESSOR: Production rate.

00:30:02.824 --> 00:30:04.490
How do we figure out
what the production

00:30:04.490 --> 00:30:05.700
rate is in this situation?

00:30:10.430 --> 00:30:13.990
That's right, the flux ware.

00:30:13.990 --> 00:30:15.020
That's right.

00:30:15.020 --> 00:30:18.055
The production rate is
the flux right at or just

00:30:18.055 --> 00:30:21.310
to the right of 0.

00:30:21.310 --> 00:30:23.680
Incidentally, where's
the flux maximal here?

00:30:23.680 --> 00:30:27.560
Is it maximal at A, B, or C?

00:30:27.560 --> 00:30:29.660
Ready three, two, one.

00:30:29.660 --> 00:30:30.690
You can do it verbally.

00:30:30.690 --> 00:30:31.270
Fun.

00:30:31.270 --> 00:30:33.160
A. Right.

00:30:33.160 --> 00:30:36.720
And that's because the
profile steepest here and then

00:30:36.720 --> 00:30:39.510
shallows out.

00:30:39.510 --> 00:30:41.450
So flux is decreasing here.

00:30:41.450 --> 00:30:46.110
And that's because some of the
morphogen is being degraded.

00:30:46.110 --> 00:30:49.990
So indeed, we can figure
out the production rate.

00:30:53.820 --> 00:30:54.360
Right.

00:30:54.360 --> 00:31:02.950
This is equal to the flux,
which is equal to minus

00:31:02.950 --> 00:31:06.290
DCDX at that location.

00:31:06.290 --> 00:31:08.825
Right, so the
morphogen profile M

00:31:08.825 --> 00:31:13.380
is a function of x is
some M0e to the minus x

00:31:13.380 --> 00:31:16.160
over L, where L is given by
this character of lengthscale,

00:31:16.160 --> 00:31:18.080
right?

00:31:18.080 --> 00:31:22.290
So if we ask what's DMDX?

00:31:22.290 --> 00:31:26.330
Well, it's going to
be-- we get a minus M0

00:31:26.330 --> 00:31:35.690
over L. Evaluated at x equal
to 0 just makes that go away,

00:31:35.690 --> 00:31:38.640
so we end up with this.

00:31:38.640 --> 00:31:42.030
So you figure out
what flux is, right?

00:31:42.030 --> 00:31:45.310
Yeah, so, it's just an extra
couple terms, it's fine.

00:31:45.310 --> 00:31:47.450
But that would be what
would typically be constant

00:31:47.450 --> 00:31:51.800
because there might be
some RNA deposit there

00:31:51.800 --> 00:31:56.110
or if it's actually
transcription off of the genes

00:31:56.110 --> 00:32:00.230
at in the cells in
this location and then

00:32:00.230 --> 00:32:03.538
it's based on whether there's
one or two copies and so forth.

00:32:09.990 --> 00:32:14.630
So this is all fine, except
that this thing is not robust.

00:32:14.630 --> 00:32:17.647
It changes in M0 or
this production rate.

00:32:17.647 --> 00:32:19.730
Whereas in many cases,
what we seek experimentally

00:32:19.730 --> 00:32:23.670
is that if we, for example,
have the production rate,

00:32:23.670 --> 00:32:26.410
then the profile
that we see out here

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:29.511
is somehow remarkably similar.

00:32:29.511 --> 00:32:30.010
Yes?

00:32:30.010 --> 00:32:31.978
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:32:35.172 --> 00:32:35.880
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:32:35.880 --> 00:32:38.940
Yeah, OK.

00:32:38.940 --> 00:32:41.980
So I'd say that in
many cases, it's

00:32:41.980 --> 00:32:46.500
not that it's directly
this M squared business.

00:32:46.500 --> 00:32:50.230
But there are a number of
cases in Drosophila, where

00:32:50.230 --> 00:32:53.060
they actually do see this.

00:32:53.060 --> 00:33:00.310
In many cases, it was a self
enhanced degradation but not

00:33:00.310 --> 00:33:03.690
that it was directly, it was
via binding to a receptor.

00:33:03.690 --> 00:33:07.180
So this was seen in
patch lists together.

00:33:07.180 --> 00:33:15.060
I want to remember which
were the models that-- I'm

00:33:15.060 --> 00:33:17.310
worried I'm always doing it
get so it's like patchless

00:33:17.310 --> 00:33:20.780
and frizzled, or-- are
there any Drosophila people

00:33:20.780 --> 00:33:24.650
here that came up with
these crazy names?

00:33:31.830 --> 00:33:33.700
All right, yeah, so
I always got confused

00:33:33.700 --> 00:33:35.857
which are the
morphogens and which

00:33:35.857 --> 00:33:37.440
are the receptors
in these situations.

00:33:37.440 --> 00:33:41.320
But I'd say that it
is something that's

00:33:41.320 --> 00:33:46.790
observed in number of
different contexts,

00:33:46.790 --> 00:33:49.050
at different stages of
development, both in Drosophila

00:33:49.050 --> 00:33:53.160
and-- they see this in the
wing as well as in the body.

00:33:53.160 --> 00:33:58.480
And so in different stages
I think it is signature.

00:33:58.480 --> 00:34:01.520
But I'm very much not a
developmental biologist.

00:34:11.500 --> 00:34:16.050
All right so the proposal that
[INAUDIBLE] suggests as a way

00:34:16.050 --> 00:34:23.540
to make this thing more robust
is to somehow change this term.

00:34:23.540 --> 00:34:30.429
Now, the goal in all this was
to have some degradation rate.

00:34:30.429 --> 00:34:33.570
And he writes it as F is
a function concentration

00:34:33.570 --> 00:34:35.710
M. In principle,
this thing could

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:38.370
be a function of the position
x, but he doesn't want that.

00:34:38.370 --> 00:34:40.036
And why was it that
he didn't want that?

00:34:44.642 --> 00:34:45.142
Yeah.

00:34:45.142 --> 00:34:48.723
AUDIENCE: Because we
already know [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:48.723 --> 00:34:49.639
PROFESSOR: Yes, right.

00:34:49.639 --> 00:34:51.420
So the whole goal
is that we want

00:34:51.420 --> 00:34:53.170
to start with some
situation where

00:34:53.170 --> 00:34:56.469
we don't know where we are
as a function of position x.

00:34:56.469 --> 00:34:59.504
And then from that get
some spatial information.

00:34:59.504 --> 00:35:00.920
So we really want
something that's

00:35:00.920 --> 00:35:03.210
not a function of x in there.

00:35:03.210 --> 00:35:05.947
Because then we've
already solved the problem

00:35:05.947 --> 00:35:07.155
that we're trying to address.

00:35:18.050 --> 00:35:20.060
And so one proposal
is indeed just

00:35:20.060 --> 00:35:21.660
to have something
that-- and this is

00:35:21.660 --> 00:35:24.230
very much a phenomenological
approach-- which

00:35:24.230 --> 00:35:28.250
is to have this thing be
self enhanced degradation.

00:35:32.080 --> 00:35:44.837
So the idea is that here if we
have the morphogen profile that

00:35:44.837 --> 00:35:45.920
looks something like this.

00:35:51.310 --> 00:35:52.810
There are multiple
ways you can have

00:35:52.810 --> 00:35:54.290
something that looks like this.

00:35:54.290 --> 00:35:59.040
So if along the way to
degradation, if the morphogen

00:35:59.040 --> 00:36:02.930
actually binds the receptor, but
then activates the degradation.

00:36:02.930 --> 00:36:07.590
And this is seen, for
example, in Drosophila.

00:36:07.590 --> 00:36:10.110
This is Hedgehog and Patched.

00:36:10.110 --> 00:36:15.380
So R is-- in this case,
you have the morphogen

00:36:15.380 --> 00:36:17.110
is diffusing outside the cells.

00:36:17.110 --> 00:36:20.830
It binds to the receptor,
and then the receptor

00:36:20.830 --> 00:36:24.860
activates imported
degradation of the morphogen.

00:36:24.860 --> 00:36:27.950
So it's not that the
morphogen is directly

00:36:27.950 --> 00:36:31.980
leading to its own degradation,
but it's via some network here.

00:36:31.980 --> 00:36:34.695
And there was another
one that they talk about,

00:36:34.695 --> 00:36:40.710
which is that, when the
degradation is mediated by 2.

00:36:40.710 --> 00:36:42.640
These look like this,
and this is in context.

00:36:42.640 --> 00:36:46.260
And this is again Drosophila,
but you could probably

00:36:46.260 --> 00:36:47.650
guess what this thing does.

00:36:51.410 --> 00:36:53.460
And so it is a wing
development as well.

00:36:58.646 --> 00:37:01.020
If you write down an actual
model of one of these things,

00:37:01.020 --> 00:37:02.260
and you could play
with it and see

00:37:02.260 --> 00:37:03.730
where you're going to get
something that's going to look

00:37:03.730 --> 00:37:05.700
like an M squared type term.

00:37:05.700 --> 00:37:08.714
But the nice thing about this
phenomenological approach

00:37:08.714 --> 00:37:11.005
is it kind of gives you a
sense of the kinds of effects

00:37:11.005 --> 00:37:13.239
that you should be looking
for that will enhance

00:37:13.239 --> 00:37:14.488
the robustness of the pattern.

00:37:17.240 --> 00:37:21.690
Now the key thing in this
whole discussion to remember

00:37:21.690 --> 00:37:27.970
is that if you have a
profile here, if you change,

00:37:27.970 --> 00:37:29.495
it's just somehow
translationally

00:37:29.495 --> 00:37:31.260
invarion in the sense
that since there's

00:37:31.260 --> 00:37:33.850
no information about
where you are here,

00:37:33.850 --> 00:37:35.930
these patterns can
kind of slide over.

00:37:35.930 --> 00:37:38.860
So if you change the
boundary condition M0,

00:37:38.860 --> 00:37:41.340
that's just equivalent to
sliding this over some distance

00:37:41.340 --> 00:37:44.120
and you could figure out
where everything has to go.

00:37:48.270 --> 00:37:50.990
And that's true not just
for the exponential profile,

00:37:50.990 --> 00:37:52.580
but for any of the profiles.

00:37:52.580 --> 00:37:55.460
And that's just because there's
no information about what's

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:57.910
going on once you're
inside the embryo.

00:38:00.730 --> 00:38:03.620
Can somebody give the
intuitive explanation

00:38:03.620 --> 00:38:06.490
for why some sort of self
enhanced degradation like this

00:38:06.490 --> 00:38:09.245
might make the
pattern more robust?

00:38:15.566 --> 00:38:19.030
AUDIENCE: Decrease
faster [INAUDIBLE].

00:38:19.030 --> 00:38:21.200
PROFESSOR: Decrease
faster when M is big.

00:38:21.200 --> 00:38:21.950
That's right.

00:38:21.950 --> 00:38:26.947
And so the idea is that
if you change the M0 here,

00:38:26.947 --> 00:38:28.780
for example, you double
it, then with a self

00:38:28.780 --> 00:38:30.863
enhanced degradation you
kind of quickly come back

00:38:30.863 --> 00:38:31.892
to where you were.

00:38:31.892 --> 00:38:36.340
So there's some sense that if
the pattern quickly comes down,

00:38:36.340 --> 00:38:40.280
then you can get it
being more robust.

00:38:40.280 --> 00:38:47.230
In particular, this
profile for large x

00:38:47.230 --> 00:38:50.210
in the proper regime,
this thing falls off

00:38:50.210 --> 00:38:56.540
as some A a over x squared.

00:38:56.540 --> 00:38:58.950
And indeed, one of the
problems in Murray's book

00:38:58.950 --> 00:39:02.070
is that if this is just
degrading as M to some power n,

00:39:02.070 --> 00:39:04.940
then you can calculate
what happens here.

00:39:04.940 --> 00:39:07.980
But this is some sort
of power law fall off.

00:39:16.010 --> 00:39:20.290
So of course, it's falling
off rapidly here, but not

00:39:20.290 --> 00:39:23.130
as rapidly as if it
were an exponential.

00:39:23.130 --> 00:39:25.350
And this is just like in
the case of the power law

00:39:25.350 --> 00:39:27.700
distributions of networks
that we were talking about

00:39:27.700 --> 00:39:31.110
before, that for the
exponential fall off,

00:39:31.110 --> 00:39:32.620
then it's just
very, very unlikely

00:39:32.620 --> 00:39:35.310
that you'll find some
node with many edges.

00:39:35.310 --> 00:39:39.790
Similarly here, you quickly
fall to zero here as compared

00:39:39.790 --> 00:39:41.040
to a power law distribution.

00:39:41.040 --> 00:39:46.380
So that means that you can
specify patterns out further

00:39:46.380 --> 00:39:47.070
in some sense.

00:39:54.120 --> 00:39:56.340
Are there any questions
about this basic idea

00:39:56.340 --> 00:39:57.510
and where it comes from?

00:40:06.161 --> 00:40:07.910
I think the discussion
in [INAUDIBLE] book

00:40:07.910 --> 00:40:09.820
is actually reasonable.

00:40:09.820 --> 00:40:14.960
So I don't really want to
spend too much time on it.

00:40:14.960 --> 00:40:19.100
In the context of
the eldar model

00:40:19.100 --> 00:40:24.014
that was from the last
section of that chapter.

00:40:24.014 --> 00:40:25.430
One thing I just
want to highlight

00:40:25.430 --> 00:40:31.360
is that it's useful to be
able to look at these models,

00:40:31.360 --> 00:40:33.580
and from the equations
that you see-- for example,

00:40:33.580 --> 00:40:35.440
the supplemental
material of a paper--

00:40:35.440 --> 00:40:39.160
make sure you are very clear
about what assumptions they've

00:40:39.160 --> 00:40:42.630
made in getting to this model.

00:40:42.630 --> 00:40:49.615
And so maybe we'll just spend a
few minutes talking about this.

00:40:52.530 --> 00:40:56.270
So this is again a
Drosphil embryo two,

00:40:56.270 --> 00:41:02.970
two and a half hours
after fertilization

00:41:02.970 --> 00:41:09.710
where at that stage, you
really have the embryo that

00:41:09.710 --> 00:41:13.020
looks like a-- we're trying
to understand the patterning

00:41:13.020 --> 00:41:17.060
around the front back.

00:41:17.060 --> 00:41:19.810
So we think about diffusion
along in one dimension,

00:41:19.810 --> 00:41:23.180
but it's really around
this radial direction.

00:41:23.180 --> 00:41:28.290
And in particular, where this is
trying to understand patterning

00:41:28.290 --> 00:41:29.330
in the dorsal region.

00:41:32.690 --> 00:41:36.810
And what we have is
a situation where we

00:41:36.810 --> 00:41:40.610
have this protease inhibitor.

00:41:40.610 --> 00:41:43.090
And so the protease
distributed uniformly.

00:41:43.090 --> 00:41:46.210
Inhibitor starts out
out there, and then we

00:41:46.210 --> 00:41:48.820
have the morphogen that
somehow starts out in here.

00:41:48.820 --> 00:41:50.650
And we want to end
up with a situation

00:41:50.650 --> 00:41:55.090
where the morphogen profile in
here is kind of well defined.

00:41:55.090 --> 00:41:56.590
So where you just
have the morphogen

00:41:56.590 --> 00:41:59.401
at the center of
this dorsal region.

00:42:02.840 --> 00:42:05.490
And then we have diffusion
of these inhibitors

00:42:05.490 --> 00:42:07.710
coming in and then the
morphogen coming out.

00:42:07.710 --> 00:42:13.040
And the question is, how
can we make sense of this?

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:19.220
And if you look at the equations
that they write down-- So

00:42:19.220 --> 00:42:20.770
we have diffusion
of the inhibitor.

00:42:33.350 --> 00:42:36.950
This is the complex
of the inhibitor

00:42:36.950 --> 00:42:40.660
and the morphogen-- complex c.

00:43:10.610 --> 00:43:13.380
And so this is a case
where they wrote down

00:43:13.380 --> 00:43:15.950
what they basically knew
about the biologists system.

00:43:15.950 --> 00:43:19.130
And then they asked, well,
what range of parameters

00:43:19.130 --> 00:43:26.690
would lead to a robust pattern
of the morphogen in here,

00:43:26.690 --> 00:43:30.340
if you vary things such as the
total concentration inhibitor,

00:43:30.340 --> 00:43:32.130
the morphogen or the protease?

00:43:36.400 --> 00:43:39.540
So we have diffusion of each
of these things, the inhibitor,

00:43:39.540 --> 00:43:42.690
the morphogen complex.

00:43:42.690 --> 00:43:44.670
We're not going to worry
about the protease,

00:43:44.670 --> 00:43:46.645
because this thing is
uniformly distributed.

00:43:46.645 --> 00:43:49.020
You can argue about whether
that's the right thing to do,

00:43:49.020 --> 00:43:51.350
but that's based on the model.

00:43:51.350 --> 00:43:54.920
So we have diffusion
of each of these guys.

00:43:54.920 --> 00:43:56.745
Can somebody say
what's going on here?

00:44:07.870 --> 00:44:10.304
What are these things
trying to capture?

00:44:10.304 --> 00:44:10.804
John?

00:44:10.804 --> 00:44:12.414
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:12.414 --> 00:44:13.830
PROFESSOR: So this
is just saying,

00:44:13.830 --> 00:44:17.412
OK, the complex is formed
as a result of binding

00:44:17.412 --> 00:44:18.870
of the inhibitor
and the morphogen.

00:44:18.870 --> 00:44:21.080
It's proportional to
concentration those two things,

00:44:21.080 --> 00:44:24.080
at that particular position
at the particular time.

00:44:24.080 --> 00:44:28.820
And just remember that any
time that you create something,

00:44:28.820 --> 00:44:31.130
if you have binding at
two things together,

00:44:31.130 --> 00:44:34.875
then you have to consider
these things going away.

00:44:34.875 --> 00:44:36.850
And it's not they're
being degraded,

00:44:36.850 --> 00:44:39.482
it's just that they're
forming this complex.

00:44:39.482 --> 00:44:40.940
So in these equations
you just have

00:44:40.940 --> 00:44:42.523
to be very careful
about keeping track

00:44:42.523 --> 00:44:44.624
of which things are
really going away

00:44:44.624 --> 00:44:46.290
and which things are
just changing form.

00:44:46.290 --> 00:44:46.772
Yeah?

00:44:46.772 --> 00:44:47.688
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:53.580 --> 00:44:55.930
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:44:55.930 --> 00:45:00.540
You're saying why that
there's not a minus term?

00:45:00.540 --> 00:45:02.242
So this is an assumption.

00:45:02.242 --> 00:45:03.700
And I think this
is a kind of thing

00:45:03.700 --> 00:45:06.300
that you have to be clear
about in any of these,

00:45:06.300 --> 00:45:09.440
because that's always going
to occur at some rate.

00:45:09.440 --> 00:45:12.830
And the assumption is
that this is dominant.

00:45:16.154 --> 00:45:18.320
And then just be clear in
words, what is this thing?

00:45:27.554 --> 00:45:30.202
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:30.202 --> 00:45:30.910
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:45:30.910 --> 00:45:32.900
The protease.

00:45:32.900 --> 00:45:34.949
And you're saying
cleaving inhibitor.

00:45:34.949 --> 00:45:36.490
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
cleaving the compacts

00:45:36.490 --> 00:45:39.372
by degrading the [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:39.372 --> 00:45:40.080
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:45:40.080 --> 00:45:43.340
So at a rate proportional to
the Proteus concentration--

00:45:43.340 --> 00:45:47.519
the complex concentration--
this complex goes away.

00:45:47.519 --> 00:45:49.810
Now the question is we have
to figure out where it went

00:45:49.810 --> 00:45:52.180
or what happened, right?

00:45:52.180 --> 00:45:54.210
Well we have a
minus alpha c here

00:45:54.210 --> 00:45:56.750
but then we have a
plus alpha c here.

00:45:56.750 --> 00:46:00.570
But this isn't the
morphogen right.

00:46:00.570 --> 00:46:05.020
This is at the rate
that the complex somehow

00:46:05.020 --> 00:46:07.180
is being disappeared
by the protease,

00:46:07.180 --> 00:46:11.340
the morphogen is appearing.

00:46:11.340 --> 00:46:15.620
But then, we don't have
the same term here.

00:46:15.620 --> 00:46:19.270
And that's how you know that
what the protease is doing

00:46:19.270 --> 00:46:26.670
is it's degrading the inhibitor
as part of the complex.

00:46:26.670 --> 00:46:28.070
So by looking at
these equations,

00:46:28.070 --> 00:46:30.710
you can actually figure out
what are the assumptions that

00:46:30.710 --> 00:46:32.805
have been made of
what the biology is

00:46:32.805 --> 00:46:33.960
that's being captured here.

00:46:33.960 --> 00:46:36.209
But in many cases, there are
assumptions of what's big

00:46:36.209 --> 00:46:38.547
and what's small.

00:46:38.547 --> 00:46:39.880
And then what's this thing here?

00:46:50.050 --> 00:46:52.647
Somebody else that has not
yet-- do these equations

00:46:52.647 --> 00:46:53.230
look familiar?

00:46:55.920 --> 00:46:56.981
Yes, please.

00:46:56.981 --> 00:47:00.750
AUDIENCE: It's the
protease [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:00.750 --> 00:47:01.750
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:47:01.750 --> 00:47:05.380
It's the protease degrading the
inhibitor when the inhibitor is

00:47:05.380 --> 00:47:09.840
not down to the
morphogen. Now of course,

00:47:09.840 --> 00:47:13.540
what the authors did next
is they searched numerically

00:47:13.540 --> 00:47:16.000
across parameter space
over [INAUDIBLE] magnitude,

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:18.570
and they found that for
some parameter regime

00:47:18.570 --> 00:47:22.960
there was a robust pattern
of the morphogen developed

00:47:22.960 --> 00:47:24.879
in here.

00:47:24.879 --> 00:47:26.920
There's no reason for you
to necessarily remember

00:47:26.920 --> 00:47:29.620
which thing it was.

00:47:29.620 --> 00:47:35.070
But what they found is
that if this term went away

00:47:35.070 --> 00:47:40.340
and this term went
away, then you

00:47:40.340 --> 00:47:46.460
end up getting a robust
profile of the morphogen

00:47:46.460 --> 00:47:49.430
against changes in the
overall morphogen inhibitor

00:47:49.430 --> 00:47:50.760
concentration.

00:47:50.760 --> 00:47:52.860
Now this is pretty
weird, I would say.

00:47:55.192 --> 00:47:57.150
I don't know, do you
think-- is this one weird?

00:48:01.830 --> 00:48:03.910
Weirdness is in the
eye of the beholder.

00:48:03.910 --> 00:48:06.520
But I would say it's
not so shocking.

00:48:11.650 --> 00:48:15.465
Can somebody say verbally
what this would correspond to?

00:48:15.465 --> 00:48:17.671
AUDIENCE: The protease
doesn't degrade the inhibitor

00:48:17.671 --> 00:48:18.170
on its own.

00:48:18.170 --> 00:48:19.800
PROFESSOR: That's right,
the protease doesn't degrade

00:48:19.800 --> 00:48:21.310
the inhibitor on
its own, only when

00:48:21.310 --> 00:48:23.560
it's part of the complex
with the morphogen.

00:48:23.560 --> 00:48:25.780
And independently there was
experimental data already

00:48:25.780 --> 00:48:26.821
indicating that was true.

00:48:26.821 --> 00:48:28.780
So you could have if
you want to just written

00:48:28.780 --> 00:48:31.285
the model without that,
because there was already

00:48:31.285 --> 00:48:32.120
evidence for that.

00:48:32.120 --> 00:48:39.190
But as I said, this is
a pretty weird thing.

00:48:39.190 --> 00:48:43.180
And so, this would be saying
that, for some reason,

00:48:43.180 --> 00:48:49.940
diffusion of the morphogen
on its own is very small.

00:48:49.940 --> 00:48:52.280
In particular, small compared
diffusion of the morphogen

00:48:52.280 --> 00:48:53.195
when it's a complex.

00:48:58.190 --> 00:49:01.499
Now can somebody say why I
might think that's weird?

00:49:01.499 --> 00:49:03.040
You don't have to
believe it's weird.

00:49:08.752 --> 00:49:10.755
AUDIENCE: You'd think
bigger is better.

00:49:10.755 --> 00:49:12.210
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:49:12.210 --> 00:49:13.102
Exactly.

00:49:13.102 --> 00:49:15.310
This is saying, well, when
it's complex, it's bigger,

00:49:15.310 --> 00:49:16.800
it's somehow diffusing faster.

00:49:16.800 --> 00:49:22.750
So this would not happen do
the simple Stokes type drag.

00:49:22.750 --> 00:49:24.940
This would have to be biology.

00:49:28.776 --> 00:49:31.150
Somebody's biology is allowed
to do anything that doesn't

00:49:31.150 --> 00:49:32.550
violate the laws of physics.

00:49:32.550 --> 00:49:35.720
Indeed, later there was
experimental evidence

00:49:35.720 --> 00:49:39.015
of something like this
was actually happening.

00:49:39.015 --> 00:49:40.670
And you could
imagine having either

00:49:40.670 --> 00:49:44.530
from sort of active transport
type dynamics for the complex,

00:49:44.530 --> 00:49:52.380
or from binding type
dynamics of the morphogen.

00:49:52.380 --> 00:49:54.650
I think the key thing to
take from this example

00:49:54.650 --> 00:49:58.030
is just that, in
general, we would

00:49:58.030 --> 00:50:01.420
like biological function--
biology would like

00:50:01.420 --> 00:50:05.150
biological function to be
robust to things that are often

00:50:05.150 --> 00:50:06.840
fluctuating or varying.

00:50:06.840 --> 00:50:10.755
And that's one way to try to
make guesses about what might

00:50:10.755 --> 00:50:11.880
be happening in the system.

00:50:11.880 --> 00:50:14.560
This sort of
computational exercise

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:18.200
is not all a proof that this
has to be what's happening.

00:50:18.200 --> 00:50:19.700
They wrote down a
particular model--

00:50:19.700 --> 00:50:22.074
it could have been that there
are other terms they're not

00:50:22.074 --> 00:50:23.010
aware of and so forth.

00:50:23.010 --> 00:50:25.010
But it's at least a way
of generating hypotheses

00:50:25.010 --> 00:50:28.690
that you can go and test.

00:50:28.690 --> 00:50:30.840
And quite generally,
I'd also say

00:50:30.840 --> 00:50:37.030
that its essential for all
of us as consumers of models

00:50:37.030 --> 00:50:40.190
to be able to look at
some of these equations

00:50:40.190 --> 00:50:42.440
and figure out what it
is that they've assumed.

