01:10:21.390 --> 01:10:23.740
And then some of them take
a long time to go away,

01:10:23.740 --> 01:10:26.360
so then they build up and then
that's the resulting patterns

01:10:26.360 --> 01:10:27.821
that you see.

01:10:33.190 --> 01:10:35.440
So what I want to do is
just for the last 10 minutes

01:10:35.440 --> 01:10:37.520
to talk about this Min system.

01:10:37.520 --> 01:10:39.520
Because it's I think
it's a beautiful example

01:10:39.520 --> 01:10:43.780
of a combination of Systems
Biology questions together

01:10:43.780 --> 01:10:46.440
with reaction diffusion
systems, and also

01:10:46.440 --> 01:10:48.240
some beautiful in
vitro experiments

01:10:48.240 --> 01:10:53.130
that I've quite appreciated.

01:10:53.130 --> 01:10:55.660
So the question is--
imagine yourself,

01:10:55.660 --> 01:10:58.080
you've gone to all this work
right, so now you're nice

01:10:58.080 --> 01:10:59.070
and long.

01:10:59.070 --> 01:11:00.960
So you'd like to
divide into two cells.

01:11:00.960 --> 01:11:03.168
And the question is, how do
you know where to divide?

01:11:06.350 --> 01:11:10.890
So you imagine that
you're some E. coli cell.

01:11:10.890 --> 01:11:16.320
You're maybe six microns
long, everything is great.

01:11:16.320 --> 01:11:19.650
And the question is,
you want to divide?

01:11:19.650 --> 01:11:22.260
Where would you like to divide
if you're an E. coli cell?

01:11:22.260 --> 01:11:22.760
Middle.

01:11:22.760 --> 01:11:25.890
OK, so what you'd
like to do is go here.

01:11:25.890 --> 01:11:30.300
And indeed, what happens is that
there's the so-called z-ring.

01:11:30.300 --> 01:11:32.420
There's a a
pseudo-polymer protein

01:11:32.420 --> 01:11:33.946
that forms a ring
around here, then

01:11:33.946 --> 01:11:38.120
it constricts itself and
pinches off the membrane.

01:11:38.120 --> 01:11:40.250
And that's how
you get two cells.

01:11:40.250 --> 01:11:43.220
So there's this
formation of this z-ring

01:11:43.220 --> 01:11:47.480
that constricts and that's
this cell division event.

01:11:47.480 --> 01:11:50.960
The question is how do
you know where to put it?

01:11:50.960 --> 01:11:54.360
And that's what this
Min system is for.

01:11:54.360 --> 01:11:56.900
And it's, of course,
like everything

01:11:56.900 --> 01:12:01.460
in bacterial genetics, it
was identify by mutations.

01:12:05.030 --> 01:12:11.790
So the Min system it's called
that because these mutants

01:12:11.790 --> 01:12:13.370
formed so-called mini cells.

01:12:18.150 --> 01:12:21.560
If you, instead of
dividing the center where

01:12:21.560 --> 01:12:24.520
you might have two copies
of the genome here.

01:12:24.520 --> 01:12:26.770
If instead you divide
over here, then what

01:12:26.770 --> 01:12:28.810
your going to end up
with is a very long cell

01:12:28.810 --> 01:12:31.220
with two copies of the genome.

01:12:31.220 --> 01:12:35.290
You're going to end up with
this mini cell without any DNA.

01:12:35.290 --> 01:12:37.520
And those mini
cells, are they going

01:12:37.520 --> 01:12:40.120
to do well for the long term?

01:12:40.120 --> 01:12:41.060
AUDIENCE: No.

01:12:41.060 --> 01:12:42.000
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:44.430
They actually can
survive for a little bi.

01:12:44.430 --> 01:12:46.830
And people have argued
that maybe that could

01:12:46.830 --> 01:12:49.897
be useful for synthetic
biology because they still

01:12:49.897 --> 01:12:52.480
make proteins, but they're not
going to go take over the world

01:12:52.480 --> 01:12:54.790
because they don't have any DNA.

01:12:54.790 --> 01:12:57.140
But these are the
so-called mini cells

01:12:57.140 --> 01:13:02.380
that happen if you have
mutations in The min system.

01:13:02.380 --> 01:13:08.750
Now, I think the three players
are MinC, MinD, and MinE.

01:13:16.660 --> 01:13:20.080
So I think that MinA and MinB
ended up not actually existing

01:13:20.080 --> 01:13:22.970
or something, in the sense that
they identified the mutants,

01:13:22.970 --> 01:13:25.290
but then they were
wrong about something.

01:13:25.290 --> 01:13:27.720
So the three that
actually ended up

01:13:27.720 --> 01:13:30.640
being involved in the actual
Min system are C, D and E.

01:13:30.640 --> 01:13:35.606
So this MinC prevents
formation of the z-ring.

01:13:43.550 --> 01:13:46.890
Now MinD and MinE are
kind of the amazing guys.

01:13:46.890 --> 01:13:54.070
So this guy binds to the
membrane and recruits MinC.

01:14:01.930 --> 01:14:09.430
Whereas MinE-- what it does is
it pulls MinD off the membrane.

01:14:09.430 --> 01:14:15.800
So it binds to MinD and
ejects from the membrane.

01:14:22.710 --> 01:14:28.020
And what has been seen by doing
imaging in live E. coli cells

01:14:28.020 --> 01:14:31.040
with fluorescently
labeled MinD and MinE

01:14:31.040 --> 01:14:35.540
is that there are remarkable
oscillations from pole to pole.

01:14:35.540 --> 01:14:37.940
And indeed, that
doesn't require MinC,

01:14:37.940 --> 01:14:39.740
so MinC is somehow
following the others.

01:14:39.740 --> 01:14:43.420
What happens is that
MinD binds over here,

01:14:43.420 --> 01:14:46.300
then MinE binds
and pushes it off.

01:14:46.300 --> 01:14:48.110
And then the MinD
comes over here,

01:14:48.110 --> 01:14:52.140
and then MinE pulls it off,
and it goes back and forth.

01:14:52.140 --> 01:14:56.220
The period is minutes, maybe.

01:14:58.920 --> 01:15:03.600
So it's a really remarkable
thing that happens in vivo.

01:15:03.600 --> 01:15:07.060
And the idea of what's happening
is that if MinD comes here

01:15:07.060 --> 01:15:09.240
and then it comes here,
on each of the edges,

01:15:09.240 --> 01:15:11.670
then it doesn't hang
out in the middle.

01:15:11.670 --> 01:15:16.080
And that means that it's only in
the middle where MinC can then

01:15:16.080 --> 01:15:20.150
bind-- oh, sorry.

01:15:20.150 --> 01:15:22.860
Because MinC is following
MinD, then only in the middle

01:15:22.860 --> 01:15:25.750
can you form the z-ring, because
that's where MinC is not.

01:15:25.750 --> 01:15:26.250
Right.

01:15:30.450 --> 01:15:32.170
It's wonderful to do
things in live cells

01:15:32.170 --> 01:15:34.866
because that's the native
context and so forth.

01:15:34.866 --> 01:15:36.990
But I think that in some
cases, it's also wonderful

01:15:36.990 --> 01:15:39.370
if you can take
purified components

01:15:39.370 --> 01:15:42.980
and recapitulate interesting
behaviors in vitro.

01:15:42.980 --> 01:15:45.131
Because then at
least you know what

01:15:45.131 --> 01:15:51.360
is sufficient to generate
a particular kind

01:15:51.360 --> 01:15:52.890
of dynamical behavior.

01:15:52.890 --> 01:15:55.155
And because this system
had been proposes

01:15:55.155 --> 01:15:59.040
as a model system for
reaction diffusion mechanism

01:15:59.040 --> 01:16:00.360
to get this behavior.

01:16:00.360 --> 01:16:03.800
And so there's this
paper by Martin Loose,

01:16:03.800 --> 01:16:09.610
in Petra Schwille's
lab in-- where was it?

01:16:09.610 --> 01:16:12.660
In Dresden.

01:16:12.660 --> 01:16:15.990
And what they did is they took
a supported lipid bilayer-- so

01:16:15.990 --> 01:16:19.240
a membrane on
glass-- and then they

01:16:19.240 --> 01:16:23.110
added purified components
of MinD and MinE

01:16:23.110 --> 01:16:24.810
that were fluorescently labeled.

01:16:24.810 --> 01:16:28.580
And then they saw
amazing patterns,

01:16:28.580 --> 01:16:32.959
these amazing reaction
diffusion waves traveling along.

01:16:32.959 --> 01:16:34.750
Now on the first day
of lecture, I actually

01:16:34.750 --> 01:16:38.780
showed you what some of
those things look like.

01:16:38.780 --> 01:16:42.270
I didn't want to use
up the projector again,

01:16:42.270 --> 01:16:44.580
but maybe I can
pull up this movie

01:16:44.580 --> 01:16:47.730
because it is kind of fabulous.

01:16:47.730 --> 01:16:50.590
So maybe you can't see
these things very well.

01:16:50.590 --> 01:16:57.640
But this is a MinD and MinE
and an overlay of the two,

01:16:57.640 --> 01:17:01.790
imaged on a two
dimensional membrane.

01:17:01.790 --> 01:17:04.580
And the movies are just amazing.

01:17:04.580 --> 01:17:07.160
When you see this, you think
that it's a simulation.

01:17:07.160 --> 01:17:10.250
It's so incredible
watching these things go.

01:17:10.250 --> 01:17:12.720
After class, you can come
up, I can show you the paper,

01:17:12.720 --> 01:17:16.510
and you can look at the
movie in more depth.

01:17:16.510 --> 01:17:19.330
But they're really
amazing patterns,

01:17:19.330 --> 01:17:21.330
and it's patterns
that you would predict

01:17:21.330 --> 01:17:23.845
from some sort of Turing type
reaction diffusion mechanism.

01:17:28.560 --> 01:17:31.140
So there are few things
that are may be worth

01:17:31.140 --> 01:17:32.500
saying in this business.

01:17:32.500 --> 01:17:36.260
So these are fluorescently
labeled MinD, MinE.

01:17:36.260 --> 01:17:39.036
They started out with
MinD that was uniform.

01:17:39.036 --> 01:17:41.077
And then they added MinE,
and over the time scale

01:17:41.077 --> 01:17:43.770
of about an hour they started
seeing these sorts of patterns.

01:17:46.460 --> 01:17:51.150
And as maybe you expected
from the in vivo behavior,

01:17:51.150 --> 01:17:59.430
what you see are these things
where MinD looks like this,

01:17:59.430 --> 01:18:05.270
whereas MinE looks like that.

01:18:05.270 --> 01:18:08.460
And then the wave
travels here to the left.

01:18:08.460 --> 01:18:12.780
Because the MinE is ejecting
the MinD from the membrane,

01:18:12.780 --> 01:18:17.060
causing this whole
thing to move.

01:18:17.060 --> 01:18:19.180
So this is a situation
where you have

01:18:19.180 --> 01:18:22.570
both of these proteins
in the liquid.

01:18:22.570 --> 01:18:25.440
All right, so in buffer, as well
as on the membrane and they're

01:18:25.440 --> 01:18:28.020
coming on and off and so forth.

01:18:28.020 --> 01:18:30.060
And in this situation,
it's wonderful

01:18:30.060 --> 01:18:32.360
because they can do all
sorts of things like control

01:18:32.360 --> 01:18:34.560
the concentration
of MinE, and see

01:18:34.560 --> 01:18:37.920
that the velocity of
these waves changes as you

01:18:37.920 --> 01:18:39.480
change concentration in MinE.

01:18:39.480 --> 01:18:40.860
So this is a really
experimentally trackable

01:18:40.860 --> 01:18:41.430
system.

01:18:41.430 --> 01:18:43.750
And then you can ask
what kind of model

01:18:43.750 --> 01:18:45.250
would lead to that
sort of behavior?

01:18:49.160 --> 01:18:51.790
Such waves, do you think
that it requires ATP?

01:19:00.820 --> 01:19:03.540
Just for fun, we can vote
yes or no, it's all right.

01:19:03.540 --> 01:19:05.486
Ready three, two, one.

01:19:05.486 --> 01:19:06.134
AUDIENCE: Yes.

01:19:06.134 --> 01:19:06.800
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:19:06.800 --> 01:19:08.600
So indeed it does require ATP.

01:19:14.680 --> 01:19:18.550
And that's a general
feature of these Turing type

01:19:18.550 --> 01:19:22.277
patterns is that there is
a non-equilibrium structure

01:19:22.277 --> 01:19:22.776
formation.

01:19:28.840 --> 01:19:31.810
Now one nice thing you can
do in this sort of system

01:19:31.810 --> 01:19:33.435
is you can ask, well,
what happens if I

01:19:33.435 --> 01:19:36.310
photo bleach a particular area?

01:19:36.310 --> 01:19:37.680
So I come in and I photo bleach.

01:19:37.680 --> 01:19:43.860
So now the profile
looks like-- I locally

01:19:43.860 --> 01:19:48.160
deplete the fluorescence here.

01:19:48.160 --> 01:19:51.860
Question is, will this move
together with the traveling

01:19:51.860 --> 01:19:54.280
wave, or does it stay fixed?

01:19:56.960 --> 01:19:59.830
And in these mechanisms, do
you think should this locally

01:19:59.830 --> 01:20:02.696
depleted area, should it move
or should it stay where it is?

01:20:02.696 --> 01:20:03.987
Do you understand the question?

01:20:06.930 --> 01:20:07.960
Move, yes/no.

01:20:07.960 --> 01:20:10.044
Ready three, two, one.

01:20:10.044 --> 01:20:10.960
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:20:14.320 --> 01:20:17.430
PROFESSOR: It
actually doesn't move.

01:20:17.430 --> 01:20:19.336
Depleted area doesn't move.

01:20:27.070 --> 01:20:29.650
And this is just a reflection.

01:20:29.650 --> 01:20:33.032
These waves are not the result
of individual molecules moving

01:20:33.032 --> 01:20:33.990
together with the wave.

01:20:37.040 --> 01:20:41.130
A wave like what you see in
the ocean, or on a stream,

01:20:41.130 --> 01:20:41.940
or what not.

01:20:41.940 --> 01:20:48.657
So the motion is a result of
the individual molecules coming

01:20:48.657 --> 01:20:50.490
and going and communicating
with each other,

01:20:50.490 --> 01:20:53.270
but it's not a reflection
of actual molecules

01:20:53.270 --> 01:20:55.210
having directed motion.

01:20:55.210 --> 01:20:58.580
Because indeed,
there's no mechanism

01:20:58.580 --> 01:21:02.070
in these models for
directed motion.

01:21:02.070 --> 01:21:05.700
What you see is that
in all these models,

01:21:05.700 --> 01:21:11.070
the only thing that is
a function of position

01:21:11.070 --> 01:21:12.760
is diffusion terms.

01:21:12.760 --> 01:21:18.070
So it's all random diffusion,
but then you get global motion.

